<p><a href="#sdfootnote24anc" name="sdfootnote24sym">24</a>As Shell convincingly shows, Thayer's concept of camouflage was directly tied to his use of photography. Not only were his arguments supported by staged photographs, but also the way he imagined hunting prey – and hiding from the predator – was based on a static model of observing: as in photography. Thayer's “crucial moments” could be analyzed in relation to Henri Cartier Bresson's “decisive moments.” One of the strongest criticisms waged at Thayer was precisely the fact that neither animal hunting nor modern warfare are static, but dynamic.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote25anc" name="sdfootnote25sym">25</a>Abbott H. Thayer, “The Law That Underlies Protective Coloration,” <em>The Auk </em>13 (1896): 125, 128. The phenomenon of mimicry has a large literature in the humanities and especially in psychoanalysis. Most famously, it has been employed by Roger Caillois in his work on psychastenia and by Jacques Lacan. See Roger Caillois, “Mimicry and Legendary Psychasthenia,” trans. J. Shepley, <em>October </em>31 (1984) and Jacques Lacan, “The Line of Light,” in idem, <em>The Four Fundamental Concepts of Psycho-Analysis</em>, trans. Alan Sheridan (New York: Norton, 1978), 91-104.</p>
