<p><a href="#sdfootnote48anc" name="sdfootnote48sym">48</a>In this context, it is worth recalling the acts of opposition towards being photographed in the early days of the police mug-shot practice. In <em>A Subject for the Rogues Gallery </em>(also known as <em>Photographing a Female Crook</em>), a short film from 1904, a woman is brought into the police station to be photographed. When placed in front of the camera she starts making faces and grimacing to make it impossible for the police to photograph her. See <em>Subject for Rogues Gallery, </em>dir. A.E. Weed, 1904, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0VxGqjtuJuE">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0VxGqjtuJuE</a>, accessed April 29, 2014.</p>
